abindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Aug 23, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104etu1665703249143.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/etu1665703249143.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/etu1665703249143.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"etu1665703249143\" role=\"article\">\n<div class=\"body conbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Enable two-phase commit functionality.</p>\n<section class=\"section refsyn\" id=\"etu1665703249143__topic_d143501e1_d143502e1_d143503e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"etu1665703249143__p_d143504e1_d143505e1_d143506e1\">\n<span class=\"keyword cmdname\">$TWO_PHASE_COMMIT</span>\n</p>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"etu1665703249143__section_svr_slm_lwb\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d109205e59\">Defaults</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table class=\"table\" count-columns=\"2\" id=\"etu1665703249143__table_d17318e1_d17319e1_d17320e1\"><caption></caption><colgroup><col/><col/></colgroup><tbody class=\"tbody\">\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">Assignment file: </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">Assignment file of the application or Uniface\n                        Server that runs that two-phase commit connector </td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">Section:</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">[SETTINGS]</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">Default value:</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">None</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"etu1665703249143__section_nrm_vlm_lwb\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d109205e105\">Description</h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"etu1665703249143__p_d143513e1_d143514e1_d143515e1\"><span class=\"keyword cmdname\">$TWO_PHASE_COMMIT</span> causes Uniface\n            to use a two-phase commit for those DBMSs which support it. Using a two-phase commit can\n            carry a (DBMS) performance penalty, so it is advisable to use it only with those\n            applications which require it. You do not need to assign a value to\n               <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">$TWO_PHASE_COMMIT</span>.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"etu1665703249143__p_d143516e1_d143517e1_d143518e1\">This setting should be placed in the assignment\n            file of the application or Uniface Server that runs that two-phase commit connector, not\n            necessarily in the client application. The client application always handles two-phase\n            commit logic, regardless of whether the setting is locally defined. However, if there is\n            a local database that supports two-phase commit, the setting should be defined on the\n            client.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/bbx1665702720076.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Two-Phase Commit</a><p>Physical referential integrity across more than one database (that is, distributed databases) requires a two-phase commit. This is because there is one separate commit per database (although Uniface can issue one commit to commit a path which leads to several databases). A two-phase commit allows the DBMS to ensure that modifications written to several physical locations can all be written correctly before issuing the final commit.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2527304\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2527304\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "$TWO_PHASE_COMMIT Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Aug 23, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Enable two-phase commit functionality. $TWO_PHASE_COMMIT Defaults Assignment file: Assignment file of the application or Uniface Server that runs that two-phase commit connector Section: [SETTINGS] Default value: None Description $TWO_PHASE_COMMIT causes Uniface to use a two-phase commit for those DBMSs which support it. Using a two-phase commit can carry a (DBMS) performance penalty, so it is advisable to use it only with those applications which require it. You do not need to assign a value to $TWO_PHASE_COMMIT . This setting should be placed in the assignment file of the application or Uniface Server that runs that two-phase commit connector, not necessarily in the client application. The client application always handles two-phase commit logic, regardless of whether the setting is locally defined. However, if there is a local database that supports two-phase commit, the setting should be defined on the client. Related Links Two-Phase Commit Physical referential integrity across more than one database (that is, distributed databases) requires a two-phase commit. This is because there is one separate commit per database (although Uniface can issue one commit to commit a path which leads to several databases). A two-phase commit allows the DBMS to ensure that modifications written to several physical locations can all be written correctly before issuing the final commit. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}